3. Step-by-Step Deployment Guide from Scratch
Step A: Initialize Your Repository
Open your terminal inside your project folder and run the following commands to initialize Git and add your files:

Bash
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit: Multi-stage AWS deployment architecture"
Step B: Save Your Credentials Safely
Never hardcode your AWS access keys in your YAML files!

Go to your repository on GitHub.

Navigate to Settings ──► Secrets and variables ──► Actions.

Click New repository secret and add:

AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID: Your AWS access key.

AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY: Your AWS secret key.

Step C: Push to Production
Link your local folder to GitHub and push:

Bash
git remote add origin <your-github-repo-url>
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main
Once pushed, click on the Actions tab in GitHub. You will see all three stages light up one by one. If Stage 1 or Stage 2 encounters an error, the pipeline will immediately halt, protecting your production servers from incorrect configurations.
================

In GitHub Actions, we achieve this by defining separate jobs and using the needs keyword to force them to run in a strict sequence.

Here is the complete, production-ready code for your .github/workflows/main.yml.

The Full Code: .github/workflows/main.yml
YAML
name: AWS Instance File Deployment

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main

jobs:
  # ==========================================
  # STAGE 1: Run Python Script Locally
  # ==========================================
  run_python_script:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - name: Checkout Code
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Set up Python
        uses: actions/setup-python@v5
        with:
          python-version: '3.10'

      - name: Run HelloWorld Script
        run: |
          python helloworld.py

  # ==========================================
  # STAGE 2: Validate AWS & SSM Connectivity
  # ==========================================
  check_aws_ssm:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    needs: run_python_script  # <-- Only runs if Stage 1 succeeds
    steps:
      - name: Checkout Code
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Configure AWS Credentials
        uses: aws-actions/configure-aws-credentials@v4
        with:
          aws-access-key-id: ${{ secrets.AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID }}
          aws-secret-access-key: ${{ secrets.AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY }}
          aws-region: us-east-1

      # This verifies that your 2 target hosts are actually online and responding to SSM
      # before Ansible attempts to run.
      name: Verify EC2 SSM Status
      run: |
        echo "Checking for running instances tagged Environment=Production..."
        INSTANCE_IDS=$(aws ec2 describe-instances \
          --filters "Name=tag:Environment,Values=Production" "Name=instance-state-name,Values=running" \
          --query "Reservations[*].Instances[*].InstanceId" --output text)
        
        if [ -z "$INSTANCE_IDS" ]; then
          echo "ERROR: No production instances found!"
          exit 1
        fi

        echo "Verifying SSM connectivity for instances: $INSTANCE_IDS"
        for id in $INSTANCE_IDS; do
          STATUS=$(aws ssm describe-instance-information --filters "Key=InstanceIds,Values=$id" --query "InstanceInformationList[0].PingStatus" --output text)
          if [ "$STATUS" != "Online" ]; then
            echo "ERROR: Instance $id is not Online in SSM! Status: $STATUS"
            exit 1
          fi
          echo "Instance $id is Online and ready."
        done

  # ==========================================
  # STAGE 3: Run Ansible Playbook
  # ==========================================
  run_ansible:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    needs: check_aws_ssm  # <-- Only runs if Stage 2 succeeds
    steps:
      - name: Checkout Code
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Configure AWS Credentials
        uses: aws-actions/configure-aws-credentials@v4
        with:
          aws-access-key-id: ${{ secrets.AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID }}
          aws-secret-access-key: ${{ secrets.AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY }}
          aws-region: us-east-1

      - name: Set up Ansible and AWS Collection
        run: |
          pip install boto3 botocore
          ansible-galaxy collection install amazon.aws
          sudo curl "https://s3.amazonaws.com/session-manager-downloads/plugin/latest/ubuntu_64bit/session-manager-plugin.deb" -o "session-manager-plugin.deb"
          sudo dpkg -i session-manager-plugin.deb

      - name: Run Ansible Playbook
        run: |
          ansible-playbook -i demo_aws_ec2.yml deploy.yml
Update to Your Ansible File (deploy.yml)
Since you mentioned you want Stage 3 to copy two files (your configuration file AND your helloworld.py file) to the 2 target hosts, update your deploy.yml playbook file to look like this:

YAML
- name: Deploy files to production hosts
  hosts: all
  gather_facts: false
  vars:
    ansible_connection: aws_ssm
  
  tasks:
    # File 1: Your original text configuration file
    - name: Create the config file on the servers
      ansible.builtin.copy:
        dest: /tmp/config.txt
        content: "Config updated via GitHub Actions pipeline on 2026-07-14\n"
        mode: '0644'

    # File 2: Copy the helloworld.py file from the repository to the EC2 hosts
    - name: Copy helloworld.py to the servers
      ansible.builtin.copy:
        src: helloworld.py
        dest: /tmp/helloworld.py
        mode: '0755'
How this workflow behaves:
Isolation: Each stage runs on a completely fresh ubuntu-latest runner instance.

Dependency Tree: Stage 2 will wait for Stage 1. Stage 3 will wait for Stage 2. If Stage 1 fails (e.g., your Python script has a syntax error), Stage 2 and Stage 3 will be canceled automatically.

Safety Layer: Stage 2 functions as a gatekeeper. It explicitly checks AWS SSM to verify your 2 hosts are healthy before handing off execution to Ansible, saving execution time if a server is offline.
